You can create a batch by [`PreparedStatement#addBatch()`][1] and execute it by [`PreparedStatement#executeBatch()`][2].

Here&#39;s a kickoff example:

    public void save(List&lt;Entity&gt; entities) throws SQLException {
        try (
            Connection connection = database.getConnection();
            PreparedStatement statement = connection.prepareStatement(SQL_INSERT);
        ) {
            int i = 0;

            for (Entity entity : entities) {
                statement.setString(1, entity.getSomeProperty());
                // ...

                statement.addBatch();
                i++;

                if (i % 1000 == 0 || i == entities.size()) {
                    statement.executeBatch(); // Execute every 1000 items.
                }
            }
        }
    }

It&#39;s executed every 1000 items because some JDBC drivers and/or DBs may have a limitation on batch length.

**See also**:

- [JDBC tutorial - Using PreparedStatement][3]
- [JDBC tutorial - Using Statement Objects for Batch Updates][4]

  [1]: http://docs.oracle.com/javase/8/docs/api/java/sql/PreparedStatement.html#addBatch--
  [2]: http://docs.oracle.com/javase/8/docs/api/java/sql/Statement.html#executeBatch--
  [3]: http://docs.oracle.com/javase/tutorial/jdbc/basics/prepared.html
  [4]: https://docs.oracle.com/javase/tutorial/jdbc/basics/retrieving.html#batch_updates

